<Project>
  <!--
    Slice 4 F-27 — build a metadata-only static library against
    PrayerApp.HostShortcuts/HostShortcuts.xcodeproj and inject the resulting
    Metadata.appintents/ directory into PrayerApp.app's bundle root via the
    documented dotnet-iOS BundleResource pipeline.

    Why a separate Xcode project:
      WFInterchangeAppRegistry / linkd resolve App Shortcut intents by HOST
      bundle ID (com.multithreadedllc.prayercards). The host has no Swift
      sources, so appintentsmetadataprocessor never runs against it. Apple DTS
      (forums thread 759160, Aug 2024) explicitly says App-Shortcut-backing
      intents must be in the main app target — workaround until FB14857658
      ships is to source-duplicate the intent declaration into the host.

    Why static-library (not framework, not <XcodeProject>):
      Apple bug FB13281659 (open since 2023-10-17) makes metadata extraction
      flaky when intents live in a framework shared between host + extension
      on TestFlight/ad-hoc builds. <XcodeProject> emits XCFRAMEWORK and
      forwards as <NativeReference>. Static lib's .a is discarded; only the
      side-effect Metadata.appintents/ directory matters, and static libs DO
      trigger appintentsmetadataprocessor (verified on Xcode 26 / iOS 26.4).

    Why CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn + LogicalName:
      Xamarin maintainer rolfbjarne in dotnet/macios#11984 prescribes exactly
      this pattern for adding BundleResource items from a target body:
        <CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn>
          $(CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn);
          MyTarget;
        </CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn>
      The Xamarin.MacDev.Tasks BundleResource.GetLogicalName method (in
      msbuild/Xamarin.MacDev.Tasks/BundleResource.cs) reads %(LogicalName)
      metadata FIRST when computing destination path inside the bundle —
      NOT %(Link). LogicalName here is Xamarin's custom convention, distinct
      from the generic SDK %(Link)/%(TargetPath) keys.

    Why <NativeReference Kind="Static" ForceLoad="True">:
      Apple's runtime requires the AppShortcutsProvider Swift TYPE itself in
      the host's executable, not just its metadata description. Verified
      empirically (build 81 on iPhone 17): Metadata.appintents/ alone produces
      "Attempted to fetch Auto Shortcuts, but couldn't find the
      AppShortcutsProvider" because linkd looks for the registered Swift class
      in the host process. Apple Developer Forums thread 710552 (syatyo, Sept
      2023) prescribes "moving the file containing a concrete
      AppShortcutsProvider type to my host app target" — which for a hybrid
      MAUI app means linking the Swift static library's .a into the host's
      main executable. Microsoft Learn (Xamarin.iOS binding migration) shows
      the canonical pattern with Kind=Static + ForceLoad=True. ForceLoad keeps
      Swift symbols that have no direct C-callable references — without it the
      native linker dead-strips the AppShortcutsProvider class registration.
      LinkWithSwiftSystemLibraries=true is required so the Swift runtime libs
      are linked alongside.

    Refs:
      - https://developer.apple.com/forums/thread/759160 (Apple DTS)
      - https://developer.apple.com/forums/thread/710552 (AppShortcutsProvider link requirement)
      - https://github.com/feedback-assistant/reports/issues/425 (FB13281659)
      - https://github.com/dotnet/macios/issues/11984#issuecomment (rolfbjarne)
      - https://github.com/dotnet/macios/blob/main/msbuild/Xamarin.MacDev.Tasks/BundleResource.cs (GetLogicalName)
      - https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/migration/ios-binding-projects (NativeReference Static + ForceLoad)
      - https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/ios/building-apps/build-properties (LinkWithSwiftSystemLibraries)
  -->

  <PropertyGroup>
    <HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir>$([System.IO.Path]::GetFullPath('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\PrayerApp.HostShortcuts'))</HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir>
    <HostShortcutsTarget>HostShortcuts</HostShortcutsTarget>

    <HostShortcutsXcodeConfig Condition="'$(Configuration)' == 'Release'">Release</HostShortcutsXcodeConfig>
    <HostShortcutsXcodeConfig Condition="'$(HostShortcutsXcodeConfig)' == ''">Debug</HostShortcutsXcodeConfig>

    <HostShortcutsSdk Condition="$(RuntimeIdentifier.StartsWith('iossimulator'))">iphonesimulator</HostShortcutsSdk>
    <HostShortcutsSdk Condition="'$(HostShortcutsSdk)' == ''">iphoneos</HostShortcutsSdk>

    <HostShortcutsDerivedRoot>DerivedData/HostShortcuts/Build</HostShortcutsDerivedRoot>
    <HostShortcutsBuildOutputRel>$(HostShortcutsDerivedRoot)/Products/$(HostShortcutsXcodeConfig)-$(HostShortcutsSdk)</HostShortcutsBuildOutputRel>
    <HostShortcutsMetadataDir>$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)/$(HostShortcutsBuildOutputRel)/HostShortcuts.appintents/Metadata.appintents</HostShortcutsMetadataDir>
    <HostShortcutsStaticLib>$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)/$(HostShortcutsBuildOutputRel)/libHostShortcuts.a</HostShortcutsStaticLib>

    <!-- Stamp lives inside the per-config-per-SDK Products dir so the Inputs/Outputs
         incremental check matches the artifact paths it gates. Putting the stamp
         at a config-agnostic path causes deterministic build failures when the
         user switches Config/SDK without `dotnet clean`: Debug-iphoneos build
         touches the stamp, subsequent Release-iphoneos build sees stamp newer
         than @(_HostShortcutsSource), MSBuild skips _BuildHostShortcuts, and
         _AddHostShortcutsNativeReference registers a NativeReference at a
         path that doesn't exist for the new (Config, SDK) — linker fails.
         xcodebuild creates the parent Products dir during its own run, so the
         <Touch> after a successful <Exec> can write the stamp. -->
    <HostShortcutsBuildStamp>$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)/$(HostShortcutsBuildOutputRel)/HostShortcuts.success.stamp</HostShortcutsBuildStamp>

    <!-- Swift static library contains the AppShortcutsProvider class. The
         native linker needs Swift's system libraries when linking it into
         the host executable. Documented in Microsoft Learn build-properties. -->
    <LinkWithSwiftSystemLibraries Condition="$([MSBuild]::GetTargetPlatformIdentifier('$(TargetFramework)')) == 'ios'">true</LinkWithSwiftSystemLibraries>

    <!-- Hook our resource-collection target into the documented dotnet-iOS
         extensibility point. _CollectBundleResources reads
         $(CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn) to discover targets that contribute
         BundleResource items. iOS-only guard: this property is meaningless on
         Android. -->
    <CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn Condition="$([MSBuild]::GetTargetPlatformIdentifier('$(TargetFramework)')) == 'ios'">
      $(CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn);
      _CollectHostShortcutsBundleResources;
    </CollectBundleResourcesDependsOn>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <_HostShortcutsSource Include="$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)/HostShortcuts/**/*.swift" />
    <_HostShortcutsSource Include="$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)/HostShortcuts.xcodeproj/project.pbxproj" />
  </ItemGroup>

  <Target Name="_BuildHostShortcuts"
          Inputs="@(_HostShortcutsSource)"
          Outputs="$(HostShortcutsBuildStamp)">
    <Message Importance="high"
             Text="Slice 4 F-27: building HostShortcuts metadata-only static library ($(HostShortcutsXcodeConfig) / $(HostShortcutsSdk)) via xcodebuild" />
    <Exec WorkingDirectory="$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)"
          Command="xcodebuild -project HostShortcuts.xcodeproj -target $(HostShortcutsTarget) -configuration $(HostShortcutsXcodeConfig) -sdk $(HostShortcutsSdk) SYMROOT=$(HostShortcutsDerivedRoot)/Products OBJROOT=$(HostShortcutsDerivedRoot)/Intermediates.noindex CODE_SIGN_IDENTITY=&quot;&quot; CODE_SIGNING_REQUIRED=NO CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO build" />
    <Touch Files="$(HostShortcutsBuildStamp)" AlwaysCreate="true" />
  </Target>

  <!-- Adds @(BundleResource) items inside the target body. A top-level
       <ItemGroup> would evaluate at project load BEFORE xcodebuild produced
       the metadata files. By emitting the items inside this target — reached
       via _CollectBundleResources's DependsOnTargets chain — they are visible
       to the <CollectBundleResources> task call that follows.

       LogicalName (NOT Link) is the metadata that Xamarin.MacDev.Tasks's
       BundleResource.GetLogicalName method reads first; per dotnet/macios#11984
       this is the documented path for late-bound bundle resource injection. -->
  <Target Name="_CollectHostShortcutsBundleResources"
          DependsOnTargets="_BuildHostShortcuts">
    <ItemGroup>
      <_HostShortcutsMetadataFile Include="$(HostShortcutsMetadataDir)\**\*" />
      <BundleResource Include="@(_HostShortcutsMetadataFile)">
        <LogicalName>Metadata.appintents/%(_HostShortcutsMetadataFile.RecursiveDir)%(_HostShortcutsMetadataFile.Filename)%(_HostShortcutsMetadataFile.Extension)</LogicalName>
      </BundleResource>
    </ItemGroup>
    <Warning Text="Slice 4 F-27: Metadata.appintents/ glob produced ZERO files at $(HostShortcutsMetadataDir) — host App Shortcuts will not register"
             Condition="'@(_HostShortcutsMetadataFile)' == ''" />
  </Target>

  <!-- Add libHostShortcuts.a as a static NativeReference so the host's native
       linker links it into the main executable. ForceLoad=True keeps Swift
       symbols that have no direct C-callable references (the AppShortcutsProvider
       Swift class registration runs in static initializers, which would
       otherwise be dead-stripped). DependsOnTargets ensures xcodebuild has
       produced the .a before we register it. BeforeTargets="_ExpandNativeReferences"
       ensures the SDK sees our NativeReference when it builds the linker
       inputs. Late-binding inside a target body avoids the project-load
       evaluation order problem (the .a doesn't exist when csproj loads). -->
  <Target Name="_AddHostShortcutsNativeReference"
          BeforeTargets="_ExpandNativeReferences"
          DependsOnTargets="_BuildHostShortcuts">
    <ItemGroup>
      <NativeReference Include="$(HostShortcutsStaticLib)">
        <Kind>Static</Kind>
        <ForceLoad>True</ForceLoad>
        <SmartLink>False</SmartLink>
      </NativeReference>
    </ItemGroup>
    <Warning Text="Slice 4 F-27: libHostShortcuts.a not found at $(HostShortcutsStaticLib) — host AppShortcutsProvider Swift class will not be linked"
             Condition="!Exists('$(HostShortcutsStaticLib)')" />
  </Target>

  <Target Name="_CleanHostShortcuts" AfterTargets="Clean">
    <RemoveDir Directories="$(HostShortcutsXcodeProjectDir)/DerivedData" />
  </Target>
</Project>
